# Networking Key Terminology

## Core Protocols and Terms

- WEP — Wired Equivalent Privacy

A wireless security protocol formerly used to secure Wi-Fi networks. It is now considered weak and outdated.

### SSH — Secure Shell

A secure network protocol used to remotely log into systems and execute commands safely.

### FTP — File Transfer Protocol

Used to transfer files between systems over a network.

### SMTP — Simple Mail Transfer Protocol

Used to send and receive email messages.

### HTTP — Hypertext Transfer Protocol

Client-server protocol used to transfer web pages and data across the internet.

### SMB — Server Message Block

Used for sharing files, printers, and resources across a network.

### NFS — Network File System

Allows users to access files over a network as if they were local.

### SNMP — Simple Network Management Protocol

Used for monitoring and managing network devices.

### WPA — Wi-Fi Protected Access

Wireless security protocol that protects Wi-Fi using stronger security than WEP.

### TKIP — Temporal Key Integrity Protocol

Older wireless security protocol used with WPA; less secure than modern standards.

### NTP — Network Time Protocol

Used to synchronize time across computers and devices on a network.

### VLAN — Virtual Local Area Network

Logically separates one physical network into multiple smaller networks.

### VTP — VLAN Trunking Protocol

Layer 2 Cisco protocol used to manage VLAN configurations across switches.

### RIP — Routing Information Protocol

A distance-vector routing protocol used in LANs and WANs.

### OSPF — Open Shortest Path First

An interior gateway protocol used for routing within a single autonomous system.

### IGRP — Interior Gateway Routing Protocol

Cisco proprietary routing protocol for routing within autonomous systems.

### EIGRP — Enhanced Interior Gateway Routing Protocol

Advanced Cisco routing protocol for efficient IP traffic routing.

### PGP — Pretty Good Privacy

Encryption system used to secure emails, files, and sensitive data.

### NNTP — Network News Transfer Protocol

Used for distributing and retrieving messages in internet newsgroups.

### CDP — Cisco Discovery Protocol

Cisco proprietary protocol for discovering and managing Cisco devices.

### HSRP — Hot Standby Router Protocol

Provides router redundancy in case the main router fails.

### VRRP — Virtual Router Redundancy Protocol

Provides automatic backup router assignment for network reliability.

### STP — Spanning Tree Protocol

Prevents loops in Layer 2 Ethernet networks.

### TACACS — Terminal Access Controller Access-Control System

Provides centralized authentication, authorization, and accounting for network access.

### SIP — Session Initiation Protocol

Used to establish and terminate voice, video, and multimedia sessions.

### VOIP — Voice Over IP

Technology that allows phone calls over the internet.

### EAP — Extensible Authentication Protocol

Authentication framework supporting multiple login methods.

### LEAP — Lightweight Extensible Authentication Protocol

Cisco wireless authentication protocol based on EAP.

### PEAP — Protected Extensible Authentication Protocol

Provides encrypted authentication tunnels for secure network access.

### SMS — Systems Management Server

Used for managing systems, networks, and mobile devices.

### MBSA — Microsoft Baseline Security Analyzer

Microsoft security tool used to detect vulnerabilities in Windows systems.

### SCADA — Supervisory Control and Data Acquisition

Industrial control system used to monitor and manage industrial operations.

### VPN — Virtual Private Network

Creates a secure encrypted connection over the internet.

### IPsec — Internet Protocol Security

Provides secure encrypted communication over networks, commonly used in VPNs.

### PPTP — Point-to-Point Tunneling Protocol

Used to create encrypted tunnels for remote access.

### NAT — Network Address Translation

Allows multiple devices to share one public IP address.

### CRLF — Carriage Return Line Feed

Marks the end of a line and start of a new one in text file formats.

### AJAX — Asynchronous JavaScript and XML

Web development method for dynamic web pages using JavaScript and XML/JSON.

### ISAPI — Internet Server Application Programming Interface

Allows high-performance web extensions for web servers.

### URI — Uniform Resource Identifier

General identifier used for resources on the internet.

### URL — Uniform Resource Locator

A subset of URI that identifies the exact location of a resource online.

### IKE — Internet Key Exchange

Used in VPNs to establish secure encrypted connections.

### GRE — Generic Routing Encapsulation

Encapsulates data transmitted inside VPN tunnels.

### RSH — Remote Shell

Unix program used to execute commands on a remote system.

Internet Key Exchange	IKE	IKE is a protocol used to set up a secure connection between two computers. It is used in virtual private networks (VPNs) to provide authentication and encryption for data transmission, protecting the data from outside eavesdropping and tampering.
Generic Routing Encapsulation	GRE	This protocol is used to encapsulate the data being transmitted within the VPN tunnel.
Remote Shell	RSH	It is a program under Unix that allows executing commands and programs on a remote computer
